00:02:36.160 --> 00:02:37.120
<v Brute>Start.</v>

00:02:37.120 --> 00:03:12.560
<v LastAir>So here's the American story. A man named Stephen Thaler created this AI system, right? He called it the Creativity Machine. Now, he didn't prompt it or tweak its output. It just spat out this painting, 'A Recent Entrance to Paradise,' all on its own! Thaler even applied for copyright listing the machine as the only author. The Copyright Office said no. So, he took it to court, went the whole route: district court, DC Circuit, even petitioned the Supreme Court. Four years of back and forth. And get this, the question they asked wasn't what you'd think.</v>

00:03:12.560 --> 00:03:50.560
<v Axiom>The Copyright Office, district court, DC Circuit — none of them were asking, "Hey, is this Creativity Machine really creative?" Instead, they dove into the nuts and bolts of the Copyright Act. You see, the Act measures copyright terms by an author's lifespan and assumes authors can own property. And when it comes to work-for-hire, it implies a human created it. What the DC Circuit found was crucial: by statutory law, all creative work needs a human author. This assumption was a given, hidden in every corner of the statute, but never named until now.</v>

00:03:50.560 --> 00:04:04.480
<v Forge>(laughs) From an architectural standpoint, it's like someone finally pointed out the beam holding everything up. No one wrote it down or put it to the test. It was just silently there for three hundred years, until suddenly, a non-mortal author came knocking.</v>

00:04:04.480 --> 00:04:14.560
<v LastAir>Wait, so you're telling me the courts never once asked if the Creativity Machine was actually, you know, creative? It was all about whether the author has a lifespan!</v>

00:04:14.560 --> 00:04:30.320
<v Axiom>Exactly. You see, this lifespan thing is structural. It defines copyright duration, inheritance, and work-for-hire concepts. Pull it out, and the whole framework collapses. Three hundred years with this buried assumption, and nobody named it until a non-mortal author came along.</v>

00:04:30.320 --> 00:04:59.760
<v Forge>This is exactly what you get, from an architectural view, when systems are built on untested fundamental assumptions. Think about the Statute of Anne, seventeen ten, or the Copyright Act, nineteen seventy-six. They were written assuming authors die. And these assumptions seep into every rule about duration, inheritance, and work-for-hire. Thaler didn't lose because AI isn't creative but because the law has no "trapdoor" for non-mortal authors. It was invisible until it wasn't.</v>

00:04:59.760 --> 00:05:08.640
<v LastAir>Ok, but hold on — does this mean the courts just skipped the creativity question? Did no one actually rule on whether AI creates creative work?</v>

00:05:08.640 --> 00:05:22.240
<v Axiom>Correct. Whether AI creativity should be protected is a policy matter. The courts only addressed a statutory issue. They're different questions entirely, though the ruling overlaps the two in public perception, the legal reasoning kept them distinct.</v>

00:05:22.240 --> 00:05:23.120
<v Brute>Who benefits?</v>

00:05:23.120 --> 00:06:01.920
<v LastAir>Exactly the right question. So, the ruling says no copyright for AI outputs. Follow the money. Who wins? It's not the artists whose work trained the AI. They can't claim rights over outputs that compete with their commissions. It's not the AI. It's the companies. Look at Bartz vs. Anthropic — one and a half billion dollars in settlements for pirated books to build the model. But that output competing with human illustrators? No legal protection there. The ruling acts like it protects human authors, but it actually shields the AI companies best.</v>

00:06:01.920 --> 00:06:27.280
<v Axiom>The EU ended up in the same spot from a different path. In January twenty twenty-six, the European Parliament's Committee on Legal Affairs voted seventeen to three, with two abstentions, to keep AI-generated content copyright-free. Different system, same result. No copyright means no royalty claims on AI outputs against the companies producing them. This makes the output layer legally clear for the industry across major Western markets.</v>

00:06:27.280 --> 00:06:53.680
<v Forge>Seventy-plus lawsuits, a billion and a half in settlements, years in court — yet the legal architecture that developed is almost perfect for companies running these models. (laughs) I'm not saying it was planned this way, but when you see the result, it looks like it. Clean intake, clean output, and no liability in between. Even if nobody wrote it down, that's pretty impressive system design.</v>

00:06:53.680 --> 00:06:54.180
<v Brute>Expected.</v>

00:06:54.180 --> 00:07:14.580
<v LastAir>So, bottom line from American courts? They didn’t decide if AI can be creative. They showed the law’s human-centric and will stay that way unless Congress makes changes. And economically? That status quo supports the AI industry more than it supports the artists who helped make it all possible.</v>

00:07:14.580 --> 00:07:16.180
<v Brute>Accurate. Congress hasn't budged.</v>

00:07:16.180 --> 00:07:35.380
<v LastAir>But here's the kicker—other countries saw this and thought different. They were asking different questions. Japan said yes back in twenty nineteen. China? Mixed responses in the same month from the same courthouse! And some communities just shrugged and said, "We were never in your framework anyway."</v>

00:07:35.380 --> 00:07:59.380
<v Axiom>Japan jumped ahead in 2019. They rewrote the Copyright Act: commercial AI training on copyrighted material is fully legal there. No consent needed, no payment required. The EU and UK only allow non-commercial data mining, but Japan said, 'Go commercial.' They made this move to boost their tech sector quickly, ignoring the consent issue that slows down others.</v>

00:07:59.380 --> 00:08:10.980
