00:09:13.380 --> 00:09:44.180
<v Forge>China's got the most fascinating architectural case. (laughs) Two provincial courts, two opposite rulings, just twelve days apart. The first one in Changshu, March seventh: Lin used Midjourney, refined his creation with Photoshop, documented it all — got copyright. Court ruled it was a unique piece. But then just twelve days later in Zhangjiagang, similar AI-created images but used a single prompt — no copyright granted. Same place, same tech, different outcome. Both final. Both valid.</v>

00:09:44.180 --> 00:09:53.780
<v LastAir>And China doesn't have a binding precedent rule, so those rulings just sit there, side by side. Neither one gets to overrule the other.</v>

00:09:53.780 --> 00:10:17.380
<v Forge>Exactly, both are final. So you can get copyright in China if you document your iterative refinement. But single prompts? Nope. The same image could be copyrighted in China and not elsewhere, just based on how it's documented. From an architectural view, regulatory loopholes are documentation strategies now. It's not about the tools. It's all about your commit log.</v>

00:10:17.380 --> 00:10:17.880
<v Brute>Heh.</v>

