00:12:36.680 --> 00:13:16.280
<v LastAir>Here's what really got me. Copyright law requires an individual author and a fixed, dated work. But oral traditions? Ceremonial knowledge? They're passed down through generations without being written down—they have no single author, no date, no fixed version. So when AI pipelines got hold of them from digitized archives or repositories, they called them public domain. Not because someone decided to steal it, but because the law can't even see them. It's not adapted to recognize these forms of expression. Communities that shared culture over centuries without copyright are the ones left exposed, without recourse anywhere.</v>

