00:13:42.280 --> 00:14:17.880
<v Axiom>The UN Declaration on the Rights of Indigenous Peoples supports the protection of cultural heritage in Article thirty-one. But it’s just a declaration, not a binding treaty—whether it gets enforced is up to countries individually. Perera's 2025 review in Big Data and Society highlights that copyright laws just can't handle communal oral traditions. And I mean this — they structurally overlook them. It's not by accident; it's designed that way. The requirement for individual authorship is not a neutral choice. It's a value judgment the law makes.</v>

00:14:17.880 --> 00:14:43.480
<v Forge>And it's a significant failure mode. These works aren't just invisible — they're only categorized as 'unprotected.' The system doesn't choose to take them; it simply can't see them as a category needing a decision. It's different from a system that sees and takes them anyway. One's ill-intent. The other's an incomplete ontology. And from an architectural view, fixing them takes entirely different approaches.</v>

00:14:43.480 --> 00:15:05.480
<v LastAir>And they're outside the scope of the UNESCO reports too—those show a twenty-four percent loss for musicians and fifty-six percent for translators by 2028. But they measure against revenue baselines in the formal economy, and communities with oral traditions usually lack that. The harm's there, it's just not measured within the current frameworks.</v>

00:15:05.480 --> 00:15:10.280
